Because this machine is something that... well, I don't like machines.
Well, first of all, what's your name?
My name is Rafael San Miguel.
Y ahora para... Bueno, la historia de su vida.
En las primeras... ¿En qué año nació usted?
Don't fight to know how many years you have, because there you go.
It's the same with the century.
Well, and... My father was... ...the superintendent of schools.
in the northern district of Tamaulipas.
Until 1913, when the revolution ended the schools.
Since then, we've come to live here in Zapata.
In those days, Zapata was the head of the county.
San Ignacio, the town that is there, is a few miles away.
It had more trade, it had more money, it had more population.
But the head of the county was Zapata, and there was La Casa de Cortes.
It was a little smaller than...
Toda esa gente que vino de Guerrero, muchos nos quedamos en Zapata y entonces Zapata se fue.
La vida que se llevaba en esos días era una vida muy quieta, muy tranquila.
No había en qué divertirse ni en qué pasearse.
And in Guerrero, before the revolution, what kind of life was there?
Guerrero, his most flourishing period was before 1900.
But when I met him, I was already going to work.
What Floreciente Guerrero did was a project called the Free Zone.
to pass to European merchandise or merchandise from the United States to pass to the peoples of the border without paying rights.
And then, when they left the people of Guerrero, they did charge rights.
That's why all the peoples of the border were rich in trade.
They had a lot of trade.
And those works came, they came to Guerrero and they went from Guerrero.
They abandoned that project and then Guerrero started to go down.
Then the revolution hit him the hardest blow of his life.

Porque francamente, en Guerrero vivían gentes que tenían muchas propiedades aquí en el condado de Zapata y hasta en el condado de Webb y en el condado de gentes muy ricas que tenían grandes ranchos y todo el producto de esos ranchos iba a dar a Guerrero.
All the money that was made in all those ranches here from Hebronville and all this region and here in part of Laredo, the owners of those ranches lived in Guerrero.
The product of those ranches was going to Guerrero.
And of course it was one of those very flourishing times.
Then it turns out that the revolution came.
Those rich people who lived in Guerrero came to live here in the United States.
Here they could attend their better ranks and they didn't come back.
And that's where the decline started faster.
And your father, for what reason did he come here?
I don't know why we were afraid of the revolution.
Dad wasn't afraid, but... Guerrero came and we came too.
Is there a lot of danger?
El 7 de abril de 1913 entró una partida revolucionaria a Guerrero en la noche y tiraron unos cuantos tiros ahí y con eso fue suficiente para que se viniera todo Guerrero para acá.
Luego nosotros nos venimos como el día 15 de abril.
We were there in Guerrero for a week or a little more and we came back.
Dad's profession, he couldn't visit schools anymore because there were no schools anymore.
And we had to make a new branch of life.
In what way did you become warriors?
There was what you call a ferry boat right in front of us.
And one would pass by and one would go to the other side.
¿Y tenía su papá tieres aquí en Texas?
Papá no, más bien la familia de mamá.
Ya, pero antes de la Revolución no.
La familia de mi mamá tenía propiedades aquí y papá tenía propiedades al otro lado.
His name is also Rafael San Miguel.
The family of Cuellar is very old in this part.
It's a very old family here.
Let me show you the tree I have here.
Well, I know that the Cuellar family comes from a captain.
And your family, what is your name?
My name is Cresencia Ramirez, my father's name is Ramirez.
And is it also an old family from here?
We also come from Spain because we come from a Ramirez, José Luis Ramirez, who was
The ones that are not from Spain, the portions of land they have here.
The family of them, my family too.
My daughter, in one of your books there are some portraits that Romero Flores gave me when we were a general for the first time.
Este es el árbol de la familia Cuellar.
El primer Cuellar que vino aquí a esta región se llamó Miguel Cuellar.
Y la esposa se llamaba Gertrude.
Before Miguel Cuellar came Bartolome Cuellar, who was the father of Miguel Cuellar.
This Miguel Cuellar was the captain.
And from Captain Cuellar came five children, among them a Domingo.
And from that Domingo came a Fernando.
And from Jose Maria came my mother.
And from me, from Mary, from Jesus.
Yes, I am also from Puebla.
No, but I want to tell you that we come from the same place, but already four or five generations away.
And for the Ramírez, they ask me that I am Ramírez.
And also, my great-great-grandfather, who knows what it would be, he was also one of those who donated the King of Spain.
And Captain Bartolomé Cuellar was also from Spain.
In what year were they here?
Yo entiendo que el primer cuéllar que vino de España hacia el Tío
And from Ascencio Cuellar came a Bartolomé Cuellar, and from that Bartolomé Cuellar came that Miguel Cuellar.
The generation is over, it's too far.
There was a Tomas San Miguel who came to Eagle Pass or to Piedras Negras.
I think he was a soldier of the Spanish Army who came to Mexico.
Pablo San Miguel, 1701 or something like that.
And from Pablo San Miguel came Ruperto San Miguel.
He came from there to Guerrero.
And from there, Ruperto San Miguel came here.
My sister, we were two, my sister and I.
My sister has a dozen, how many do you have?
Do you have more than one?
No, no, I also have a son, a son, who is 14 years old.
My son is with his father.
My husband is now writing his thesis for the doctorate.
And I have a lot of work and the son is with him to help him.
This is from his father, Rafael San Miguel, who was the director of schools in Guerrero.
In the state of Tamaulipas, but he lives in Guerrero.
This is a God of ours who was named Fernando Cuellar, just like this Fernando Cuellar who is here.
There was this Fernando Cuellar, and then came this other Fernando Cuellar.
Vivían en Guerrero antes de la Revolución, luego con la Revolución se unieron.
Bueno, si su papá tenía este trabajo con el Estado, ¿por qué vivía en Guerrero y no en Ciudad Victoria?
He was there for a long time.
No, but that was much later.
When my father was a school inspector in the north district of Tamaulipas, Tamaulipas was divided into four school districts.
The north, the center, and two in the south.
And dad visited the schools in the northern district.
And it was from here, from Nuevo Larero to Matamoros, and then over there to San Fernando, over there, all of that.
And we lived in Guerrero because that's where our family lived.
It could have been better for him to have lived in Matamoros or Novolaredo.
But since he already had his house...
And after coming here to Texas, to Zapata, what kind of work did your father have?
of being a teacher, a titular.
It was... it was... what you call surveillance.
And when we came here, dad was busy measuring land by different... and in that way, we made a new life.
Petroleum companies started to come to rent land.
And my father started a company that rented land.
And then that company became interested in renting land in Mexico.
And the region of Mexico was better known by my father.
The documentation of Mexico was better known by my father.
And then he went to live in Mexico.
They went to Mexico, the city of Mexico.
Those lands were rented here in this region.
But then, in the year 25, came the regulation of the oil law in Mexico.
in the time of General Calles, who was the one who regulated the oil law.
And all the companies had the need to have government concessions to exploit their lands.
The lands that had been contracted before the year 17 had the right to a very advantageous type of concession.
and those who had been hired between the 17th and the 25th had the right to another type of concession.
The first one was preferential, the second one was confirmatory, and the second one was preferential.
The first one was for life, it was given to the owner of the land.
The second one was given to the company that had the contract for 15 or 20 years.
And after 15 or 20 years, the oil went to the hands of the government.
For that reason, my father had to go and live in Mexico.
He stayed here because he was the one who managed the bank.
He was the one who managed the bank.
I was the first banker in Zapata, and I was the one who brought the first drinking water system to Zapata.
Yes, the old Zapata waterworks were from...
And then, my father was in Mexico until the year of 28, for example.
The year of 34, he was still in Mexico.
Well, where do you receive your education?
Of course, your father was a teacher and tried to teach me a lot of things, but I never wanted to learn them.
If I had learned half of what he wanted me to learn...
He could have learned it because he had a teacher at home.
And I was preparing to go to Monterrey to a school.
In Monterrey, when the regulations came out and there was no school anymore, there was only Venezuela.
And it happened to many people the same way.
From there to here, I studied at school in Zapata, I learned a little bit of English.
Laredo also studied there for a year.
It wasn't possible in those years.
No, not for a long time.
And your mother was already crying because she was going to school.
Frankly, in those years there were aspirations for the school.
For example, Guerrero, in a generation before mine,
He produced two or three doctors and an engineer.
But then came the revolution and we said that we couldn't go to school because of the revolution.
Y para esta generación la escuela fue muy difícil.
Fue uno de los males que hizo la revolución.
Porque muchos muchachos que estaban preparados para irse a Monterrey, a México, a Guadalajara, ya no pudieron porque el país estaba en guerra.
Y la guerra estaba, pues, 10 años.
Así es que en 10 años, pues, se pasó todo el tiempo de estudiar.

But the land was finally sold to him.

And he sold it to some cousins.
Well, frankly, I didn't want to sell it, but the lady... Oh, yes, because here very close... Is there a gymnasium?
A little closer to the gymnasium, with about six or eight people.
All the owners had to leave because the agrarian law came and took it away.
Se salieron ranchos, varios ranchitos y todo, que tenían sus terrenos.
Y entonces ellos tuvieron que irse a Guerrero, porque la ley agraria llegó ahí y se los quitó, los terrenos, y se los dio a otras personas.
Y entonces yo le dije, yo no quisiera que tu terreno le sucediera eso, mandarle que lo venga.
Y él le gusta conservar las cosas, batalló.
It's sad to leave those who were for their father.
But from there I said to him, and if the agrarians come and take him, it's sadder.
And he sold him to some cousins who live there.
Some cousins who live in Nuevo Lago.
Because I was afraid that the agrarians would leave.
And did the cousins have problems with the agrarians?
Those who live in their ranches, they don't have the agrarian law there.
But the lands that are a little uninhabited, that the owner doesn't give them a lot of heat to sustain them well, like a very big ranch, they have the agrarian law.
La ley es para dueños que no viven en tierra.
Los primos viven y son rancheros.
Sí, allí están siempre y trabajan, y tienen trabajadores que les ayudan y todo eso.

Irnos a vivir allá, pues no podía.

That's when Zapata moved to this place.
The Commission of Limits, which is international, there is a commission in Mexico, there is a commission here.
The commission on this side did not intend to change Zapata.
But in the end, someone forced them and the only thing they did was to clean the land and scratch the sunsets, mark the sunsets on the streets.
And then each one of them built their house as best they could and they paid us for the houses we had there.
And then, frankly, the people of Zapata have come to do it for their own effort.
They were lucky to have a tourist attraction, I don't know why.

There is already a very large Sajona population here.
We are already more or less the 50 or 60% of Mexicans and the 40 or 50% Sajones.

El condado de Zapata ha sido un condado de gentes muy buenas.
Nosotros decimos que la gente buena del condado de Zapata vino de Guerrero.
La verdad de las cosas es que el condado de Zapata es un pueblo, es un condado de gentes pacíficas, gentes muy buenas.
And everything that is coming right now are equally very good people.
There are no discriminatory problems of any species.
I was lucky to have a very good population and the new population that came was also very good.

There is a certain comfort, a certain security.
There is much less crime than in other parts.
It seems that here in Zapata there is none.
